The paper deals with information-theoretic concepts such as fingerprinting capacities and log-likelihood decoders, which are typically studied in the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also discusses attacks and defenses in the context of fingerprinting, which falls under the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. The use of statistical methods and group testing suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also mentions the application of fingerprinting to multimedia content, which could place it in the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of different decoders, which could be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
